@@ -134,6 +135,25 @@
 that is calling with :meth:`TaskGroup.start() <.abc.TaskGroup.start>` will be blocked
 until then. If the spawned task never calls it, then the
 :meth:`TaskGroup.start() <.abc.TaskGroup.start>` call will raise a ``RuntimeError``.
+
+If you need a :class:`~.TaskHandle` for the started task, pass ``return_handle=True``.
+The value passed to ``task_status.started()`` is then available as
+:attr:`~.TaskHandle.start_value` on the returned handle::
+
+    async def main():
+        async with create_task_group() as tg:
+            handle = await tg.start(start_some_service, 5000, return_handle=True)
+            print(handle.start_value)
+
+You can also pass a *synchronous* callable to
+:meth:`TaskGroup.start() <.abc.TaskGroup.start>`, as long as it calls
+``task_status.started()`` before returning the coroutine object to run as the task.
+This is useful for wrappers that need to complete initialization synchronously before
+the task starts running::
+
+    def start_service_sync(port: int, *, task_status: TaskStatus[None]):
+        task_status.started()
+        return run_service(port)
 
 .. note:: Unlike :meth:`~.abc.TaskGroup.start_soon`, :meth:`~.abc.TaskGroup.start` needs
    an ``await``.
